BCS Licensing -- Plain-English Summary
======================================

The BCS repository contains three kinds of material, each under a
different license. This file summarises the split; the authoritative
license texts are `LICENSE`, `data/LICENSE`, and the per-project
`LICENSE` files inside `examples/lib/**/`.

1. Software -- GPL-3.0-or-later
   -----------------------------
   The `bcs` and `bcscheck` CLI tools, the test suite (`tests/`),
   the Makefile, bash completions (`*.bash_completion`), sample
   configuration (`*.sample`), script templates
   (`examples/templates/`), man pages (`bcs.1`, `docs/BCS-bash.1`),
   and the rewritten Bash 5.2 reference (`docs/BCS-bash/`) are
   licensed under the GNU General Public License, version 3 or
   later. See `LICENSE` for the full text.

2. The Standard (prose) -- CC BY-SA 4.0
   -------------------------------------
   The Bash Coding Standard document -- everything under `data/` --
   is licensed under Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0
   International. This is a creative work (prose), and CC BY-SA
   is the license Creative Commons itself recommends for such
   material. See `data/LICENSE` for the full text.

   Promotional articles under `docs/promo/` are also CC BY-SA 4.0.

3. Bundled third-party code -- per-project LICENSE
   -----------------------------------------------
   Reference implementations under `examples/lib/**/` (cln,
   md2ansi, which, symlink, dux, ls.types, trim, post_slug,
   elapsed_time, get-chassis, stopwords.bash, en_ID, shlock) ship
   with their own `LICENSE` files -- predominantly GPL-3. Those
   licenses govern the code inside their respective directories.

   Pre-existing upstream Bash manual sources under `docs/bash5.2/`
   are preserved for reference under their original terms and are
   not relicensed by this project.

Every first-party file carries a machine-readable
`SPDX-License-Identifier` header (`GPL-3.0-or-later` for code,
`CC-BY-SA-4.0` for prose) so tooling such as REUSE and grep can
identify the license of any single file without parsing this
summary.

If you redistribute BCS or a subset of it, please preserve the
relevant LICENSE file(s) alongside the files they cover.
